    "answer": "Based on my analysis of the project artifacts available in `.swival/`, here's what I've learned about the codebase and the task:\n\n**Codebase context:** This is **VisualRelay**, a .NET 10 / Avalonia UI desktop application. UI views use XAML (`.axaml` files) with code-behind in C#. There's a `Views/Controls/Buttons/` namespace with button controls (`CommonButton`, `IconButton`, `StageCardButton`). The app has an Obsidian integration (Obsidian Bridge) that manages folder paths for linking notes/tasks to Obsidian vaults.\n\n**Task requirements:**\n1. **Reveal button** \u2014 A button that opens a folder path in the OS file manager (Finder on macOS via `open -R`, Explorer on Windows via `explorer /select,`). Needs platform-specific branching.\n2. **Centralized approach** \u2014 Any existing \"open location\" buttons should reuse the same helper, not duplicate the logic.\n3. **Label \"60\"** \u2014 Add a label showing \"60\" on the input (likely a character count or some numeric indicator).\n4. **Quotes around folder names** \u2014 Wrap folder-name references in existing labels in double quotes.\n\n---\n\n**Option A \u2014 Inline implementation in Obsidian Bridge panel**\nAdd a `Reveal` button directly in the Obsidian Bridge view/code-behind using `Process.Start(\"open\", $\"-R \\\"{folderPath}\\\"\")` (macOS) / `Process.Start(\"explorer\", $\"/select,\\\"{folderPath}\\\"\")` (Windows). Add the \"60\" label and quote-wrapping directly in the same XAML file. Least effort, but duplicates the platform-path logic if used elsewhere.\n\n**Option B \u2014 Centralized `PlatformRevealService` + reusable component**\nCreate a `PlatformRevealService` (or `IRevealService`) in the app layer that encapsulates the macOS/Windows branching. Create a small `RevealButton` Avalonia control (or extend `CommonButton`) that binds to a `FolderPath` property. Refactor the Obsidian Bridge panel to use it. Then hunt for any other existing \"open folder\" buttons (e.g., in the vault picker, task result panels) and swap them to use the same service. Separately add the \"60\" label and quotes.\n\n**Option C \u2014 Unified command infrastructure + separate concerns**\nInstead of a dedicated service, add a `RevealInExplorerCommand` static relay command (e.g., using `ReactiveUI` or `CommunityToolkit.Mvvm`) that any button can reference. Bundle the \"60\" label and quote-wrapping as a single-pass XAML/C# edit pass across the Obsidian Bridge panel(s). This is lighter than Option B but still centralizes the reveal logic.\n\n```json\n{ \"summary\": \"Improve Obsidian Bridge UX by adding a cross-platform Reveal-in-Finder/Explorer button (centralized so other panels reuse it), adding a \\\"60\\\" label to the input, and wrapping folder-name mentions in quotes. The codebase is a .NET 10 Avalonia UI app with XAML views and a Buttons/ control namespace under Views/Controls/Buttons/.\", \"options\": [\"A \u2014 Inline: add Reveal button + label + quotes directly in Obsidian Bridge panel only (fast, duplicates platform logic if reused elsewhere)\", \"B \u2014 Centralized PlatformRevealService + reusable RevealButton control; refactor Obsidian Bridge + any existing open-folder buttons to use it; add label and quotes separately\", \"C \u2014 Unified static RevealInExplorerCommand (ReactiveUI/CommunityToolkit) that any button can bind to; single edit pass for label and quotes\"] }\n```",
